The 1990 hurricane season had more storms than usual but did not
include the devastating storms of years past.  Normal rainfall in the
Sahel signaled the end of a 20-year drought and may have spanned
Gilbert in 1988 and Hugo in 1989.  Dr. William Gray, a professor of
atmospheric science in Colorado, predicts a below average hurricane
season based on below average rainfall in the Sahel and other factors.
This season there were 14 named storms, eight of them hurricanes.  The
most deadly was Diana which killed 96 people in floods and mud slides
in Mexico and caused extensive damage.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d34"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ900914-0127"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="F">
   
Dr. William Gray, a professor of atmospheric science at Colorado State
University predicted that the 1990 tropical storm season would be
above average.  Rainfall in the Sahel region of West Africa is the
indicator he uses to predict hurricanes.  Winds moving across warm
ocean air cause updrafts of air bearing sea water that turn into rain
clouds.  In the absence of moisture, the storms quickly dissipate, but
storms gather strength with additional moisture.  Comparing yearly
rainfall levels in the Sahel with the number of high-powered Atlantic
hurricanes, Dr Gray found a striking correlation.  Dr Gray said
climate changes in the Sahel result from natural weather cycles.</SUM>

